78","1400":"1400","1365":"1365","Abt 1423":"about 1423","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","1507":"1507","1429":"1429","1438":"1438","1405":"1405","Raith House, Fife, Scotland":"Raith House, Fife, Scotland","Glenbervie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Glenbervie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Glenbervie, Kincardineshire, Scotland":"Glenbervie, Kincardineshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Raith House, Fifeshire, Scotland":"Raith House, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Melville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of the various places in Normandy called Malleville, from Latin <i>mala</i> ‘bad’ + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’.","Irish (mainly Ulster): English surname adopted by bearers of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoilmhichíl</b> ‘descendant of <i>Maoilmhichil</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘devotee of (Saint) Michael’.","History: The American novelist Herman Melville (1819–91) was a descendantof the Scottish Melvilles. His maternal grandfather was the revolutionary war general Peter Gansevoort (born 1749 in Albany, NY). His paternal grandfather was Maj. Thomas Melville of Boston. Irish bearers of the name claim descent from Maol Mhichíl, a chief of Síol Muireadhaigh (County Roscommon) in the 9th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Melvin","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): variant of   Melville   with alternation of final <i>-l</i> and <i>-n</i>.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoil Mhín</b> ‘descendant of the devotee of Maoilmhín’, a personal name meaning ‘gentle chieftain’."]},{"name":"Mulville","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Melville  ."]},{"name":"Mellin","meanings":["Scottish (Glamorgan): variant of   Melville  .","German: habitational name from any of various places so called.","English: variant of   Melling  ."]},{"name":"Mulvihill","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Paddy.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoil Mhichíl</b> ‘descendant of the devotee of (Saint) Michael’. The Anglicized form was sometimes abbreviated into   Melville  ."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander Melville of Glenbervie was born in 1382, in Raith House, Fife, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Laird Thomas Walter De Melville Of Fife, was 22 and his mother, Margaret Ayr, was 17. He married Marjory Scott about 1423, in Glenbervie, Kincardineshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1468, in Glenbervie, Kincardineshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 86."},"et":{"1382–1468":"1382–1468","1400–1478":"1400–1478","1405–Female":"1405–Surnud","1438–1507":"1438–1507","1360–1429":"1360–1429","1365–Female":"1365–Surnud","1468":"1468","1478":"1478","1400":"1400","1365":"1365","Abt 1423":"umbes 1423","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","1381":"1381","1507":"1507","1429":"1429","1438":"1438","1405":"1405","Raith House, Fife, Scotland":"Raith House, Fife, Scotland","Glenbervie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Glenbervie, Aberdeenshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Glenbervie, Kincardineshire, Scotland":"Glenbervie, Kincardineshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Raith House, Fifesh